1
00:00:01,084 --> 00:00:03,628
[Konno, in English] <i>I'm pulling out</i>
<i>everything! The deal is dead!</i>

2
00:00:03,712 --> 00:00:06,131
[in English] This is all your fault!

3
00:00:06,214 --> 00:00:09,426
Let's not blame the government!

4
00:00:09,509 --> 00:00:12,595
[Manuel] <i>NLEA took all necessary action!</i>

5
00:00:12,679 --> 00:00:16,474
<i>Yet there are still plenty</i>
<i>of bad actors out to ruin things</i>

6
00:00:16,558 --> 00:00:19,144
<i>for their own agenda!</i>

7
00:00:19,227 --> 00:00:21,813
You're playing with all of us.

8
00:00:21,896 --> 00:00:24,566
[Azuelo] If Carillo is the mastermind
behind all this,

9
00:00:24,649 --> 00:00:26,151
then who's helping him?

10
00:00:26,234 --> 00:00:29,237
Do you think Agent Angeles
had anything to do with this?

11
00:00:29,320 --> 00:00:30,905
I'm not sure, sir,

12
00:00:30,989 --> 00:00:32,115
but that's my suspicion.

13
00:00:33,283 --> 00:00:35,368
- [Azuelo] <i>Where is Agent Angeles?</i>
- I don't know, sir.

14
00:00:35,452 --> 00:00:37,996
[Buster] <i>She exited the tactical van</i>
<i>before the bus exploded.</i>

15
00:00:38,079 --> 00:00:40,123
<i>She never came back.</i>
<i>I thought she'd return here.</i>

16
00:00:41,791 --> 00:00:44,127
[Jamilah] <i>I couldn't even</i>
<i>talk to you properly.</i>

17
00:00:44,210 --> 00:00:45,837
<i>I couldn't even hold you close.</i>

18
00:00:45,920 --> 00:00:47,505
Because they might suspect.

19
00:00:47,589 --> 00:00:50,842
They might uncover everything about you.

20
00:00:50,925 --> 00:00:54,095
This is why you often clashed
with Napoleon.

21
00:00:54,179 --> 00:00:56,056
<i>You acted without his authorization,</i>

22
00:00:56,139 --> 00:00:57,932
<i>as you did during the medical mission,</i>

23
00:00:58,016 --> 00:01:00,810
<i>in the explosion</i>
<i>of the M/V Doña Emilia, and more!</i>

24
00:01:00,894 --> 00:01:04,147
Victory is within our reach,
and that's all because of me!

25
00:01:04,230 --> 00:01:05,815
Did you kill your brother?

26
00:01:05,899 --> 00:01:08,943
[Manuel] <i>What's more important to me?</i>

27
00:01:09,027 --> 00:01:12,447
Blood or duty?

28
00:01:12,530 --> 00:01:15,075
[Espina] Doctor, when I blacked out,

29
00:01:15,158 --> 00:01:17,285
it felt like I was dreaming.

30
00:01:17,368 --> 00:01:19,662
[Espina] <i>In my dream, I had a brother.</i>

31
00:01:19,746 --> 00:01:21,498
<i>He was the one saving me.</i>

32
00:01:21,581 --> 00:01:23,208
<i>Could it be a childhood memory</i>

33
00:01:23,291 --> 00:01:25,752
that's now coming back to me?

34
00:01:31,716 --> 00:01:35,386
[mysterious theme music playing]

35
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:52,403
[pensive music playing]

36
00:01:55,907 --> 00:01:57,617
[Espina] <i>In my dream,</i>

37
00:01:58,493 --> 00:01:59,536
I had a brother.

38
00:02:00,245 --> 00:02:01,412
And then…

39
00:02:02,163 --> 00:02:03,498
he was the one saving me.

40
00:02:14,884 --> 00:02:17,637
[somber music playing]

41
00:02:34,195 --> 00:02:35,321
[Espina] <i>But now,</i>

42
00:02:36,364 --> 00:02:38,074
I want to know the truth.

43
00:02:39,242 --> 00:02:40,660
Who they are and…

44
00:02:41,870 --> 00:02:43,746
and what truly happened.

45
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:47,625
[dramatic sting]

46
00:02:54,883 --> 00:02:58,469
[music fades]

47
00:03:12,191 --> 00:03:13,359
- It was terrible!
- [slams bed]

48
00:03:14,319 --> 00:03:16,696
- [Edrick groaning in pain]
- [overlapping chatter]

49
00:03:17,697 --> 00:03:18,865
[cries] Help!

50
00:03:18,948 --> 00:03:20,450
I was terrified!

51
00:03:20,533 --> 00:03:22,243
[suspenseful music playing]

52
00:03:22,327 --> 00:03:23,494
But…

53
00:03:24,287 --> 00:03:27,373
not a single one of you
bothered to check on me.

54
00:03:29,375 --> 00:03:30,919
[breath quivering]

55
00:03:31,002 --> 00:03:34,505
You, Ma'am MMK… I was really scared.

56
00:03:35,673 --> 00:03:39,719
Yet I didn't hear you say,

57
00:03:39,802 --> 00:03:42,138
"Edrick, how are you holding up?"

58
00:03:42,764 --> 00:03:43,973
- [crying]
- [footsteps approaching]

59
00:03:44,057 --> 00:03:45,767
- [Maya Mae] Edrick?
- [gasps]

60
00:03:46,392 --> 00:03:49,854
- Ma'am!
- Edrick, how are you holding up?

61
00:03:50,355 --> 00:03:53,566
Oh, I'm okay, ma'am. Don't worry about me.

62
00:03:53,650 --> 00:03:55,193
Honestly, I'm totally ready
to hit the buffet again.

63
00:03:55,276 --> 00:03:58,446
Ah, really? Good. Let's go.
We have somewhere to be.

64
00:03:58,529 --> 00:04:00,031
Where are we going this time?

65
00:04:00,114 --> 00:04:02,909
Major Espina is also in this hospital.

66
00:04:02,992 --> 00:04:04,494
[in English] We need to interview him.

67
00:04:05,453 --> 00:04:09,540
- [morose music playing]
- [footsteps retreating]

68
00:04:09,624 --> 00:04:12,460
If I didn't come,
there'd be endless questions.

69
00:04:12,543 --> 00:04:13,628
[music becomes quirky]

70
00:04:13,711 --> 00:04:14,754
Fine, I'm going.

71
00:04:15,838 --> 00:04:18,049
[grunting]

72
00:04:22,971 --> 00:04:24,097
[pensive music playing]

73
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:27,392
[young Gabriel sobbing, wailing]

74
00:04:27,475 --> 00:04:29,686
Don't be scared. I'll protect you.

75
00:04:29,769 --> 00:04:32,021
Yes, brother.

76
00:04:32,105 --> 00:04:34,190
[tragic music intensifies]

77
00:04:35,108 --> 00:04:36,943
[tragic music fades]

78
00:04:39,279 --> 00:04:42,407
[somber music playing]

79
00:04:42,490 --> 00:04:46,160
Good evening, Major Allan Espina.
I'm Maya Mae Kalaw.

80
00:04:47,537 --> 00:04:48,955
I know you.

81
00:04:51,165 --> 00:04:53,751
How may I be of help to you?

82
00:04:53,835 --> 00:04:55,920
We would like to interview you.

83
00:04:58,172 --> 00:05:00,466
I'm sorry, but I don't
entertain interviews.

84
00:05:02,302 --> 00:05:05,513
[in English] Oh, okay. No problem.
Sorry, Major Espina.

85
00:05:06,097 --> 00:05:09,225
[in English] We truly, um, understand
and respect your wishes.

86
00:05:09,309 --> 00:05:12,562
Still, we're looking forward to you
granting interviews in the future.

87
00:05:15,565 --> 00:05:16,691
[in English] Thanks, anyway.

88
00:05:20,069 --> 00:05:21,571
[in English] Stop that, Edrick.

89
00:05:21,654 --> 00:05:22,572
He doesn't want to do an interview.

90
00:05:22,655 --> 00:05:24,198
[in English] Let's respect his privacy.

91
00:05:24,282 --> 00:05:25,283
Okay, ma'am.

92
00:05:25,366 --> 00:05:27,785
Sorry, Edrick can be stubborn at times.

93
00:05:28,369 --> 00:05:29,746
Sorry, Major.

94
00:05:30,538 --> 00:05:34,208
[somber music continues]

95
00:05:40,131 --> 00:05:41,174
[door clicks shut]

96
00:05:48,806 --> 00:05:50,641
I wonder how Jalil is doing.

97
00:05:51,893 --> 00:05:54,854
I'm worried about my son, Omar.

98
00:05:54,937 --> 00:05:58,066
He's going up against
some very powerful individuals.

99
00:05:58,149 --> 00:06:00,443
- [gloomy music playing]
- [sighs]

100
00:06:00,526 --> 00:06:01,527
Do you think

101
00:06:01,611 --> 00:06:05,907
your former syndicate played a role
in what happened yesterday?

102
00:06:07,325 --> 00:06:08,659
I don't know.

103
00:06:09,619 --> 00:06:11,871
I haven't been one of them
for a long time.

104
00:06:12,497 --> 00:06:16,000
How long are you going
to keep your secret, Rahman?

105
00:06:16,084 --> 00:06:17,418
Especially from Jalil.

106
00:06:19,587 --> 00:06:21,756
My mind is in chaos, Omar.

107
00:06:22,507 --> 00:06:24,258
I'm scared that

108
00:06:24,342 --> 00:06:28,387
if I tell him I'm a former member
of the syndicate,

109
00:06:29,013 --> 00:06:31,057
he'll hate me.

110
00:06:31,641 --> 00:06:33,559
Jalil loves you very much, Rahman.

111
00:06:34,769 --> 00:06:38,564
All his life, you have been his father.

112
00:06:38,648 --> 00:06:43,236
He won't judge you
just because of your mistakes in the past.

113
00:06:46,989 --> 00:06:48,282
[in Arabic] In the name of Allah.

114
00:06:51,160 --> 00:06:53,496
[phone buzzing]

115
00:06:56,124 --> 00:06:57,416
Hello, Jalil?

116
00:06:57,500 --> 00:06:59,293
- [Jalil] <i>Father…</i>
- How are you?

117
00:06:59,377 --> 00:07:00,795
[gentle music playing]

118
00:07:00,878 --> 00:07:02,171
I'm okay, Father.

119
00:07:03,506 --> 00:07:06,300
I called so you'd stop worrying.

120
00:07:08,302 --> 00:07:12,974
Good. Listen, Jalil,
you have to be more careful.

121
00:07:13,766 --> 00:07:17,395
Please be more cautious.
We worry about you all the time.

122
00:07:18,729 --> 00:07:20,565
[inhales] Yes, Father.

123
00:07:21,941 --> 00:07:23,025
I promise.

124
00:07:23,568 --> 00:07:25,194
I'm going to be more careful.

125
00:07:27,196 --> 00:07:29,991
We're almost at the end.
Just a little more,

126
00:07:30,616 --> 00:07:32,994
and our lives will be peaceful again.

127
00:07:33,619 --> 00:07:35,121
Hang in there, Father.

128
00:07:37,290 --> 00:07:39,041
The next time we meet,

129
00:07:40,751 --> 00:07:42,795
I will tell you something.

130
00:07:45,423 --> 00:07:46,674
Alright, Father.

131
00:07:47,258 --> 00:07:49,010
If I get the chance,

132
00:07:49,594 --> 00:07:51,846
I'll come and see you, okay?

133
00:07:52,555 --> 00:07:53,848
Stay safe.

134
00:07:54,515 --> 00:07:55,641
Goodbye.

135
00:08:03,774 --> 00:08:04,942
[chair rattling]

136
00:08:05,735 --> 00:08:06,986
[relieved sigh]

137
00:08:17,413 --> 00:08:18,581
- Doc.
- [chuckles]

138
00:08:19,749 --> 00:08:23,419
Your discharge papers are signed already.

139
00:08:23,503 --> 00:08:25,046
Are you truly feeling well?

140
00:08:25,546 --> 00:08:28,841
Yes, Doc. I'm okay. Thank you.

141
00:08:29,842 --> 00:08:33,679
Here. Just go easy on yourself, alright?

142
00:08:34,972 --> 00:08:36,641
[gentle music playing]

143
00:08:36,724 --> 00:08:37,683
Take care.

144
00:08:39,101 --> 00:08:41,521
I will. Thank you.

145
00:08:42,522 --> 00:08:43,731
I'll go now.

146
00:08:47,026 --> 00:08:48,194
Thank you.

147
00:08:58,246 --> 00:09:00,122
[mellow music playing]

148
00:09:04,001 --> 00:09:07,213
[knife scraping]

149
00:09:07,296 --> 00:09:08,798
- Look at him.
- [sighs]

150
00:09:08,881 --> 00:09:11,509
- Mister Abet's getting old.
- [chuckles softly]

151
00:09:11,592 --> 00:09:14,720
Hey, only water buffaloes age!

152
00:09:14,804 --> 00:09:16,389
[chuckles] Papa!

153
00:09:16,472 --> 00:09:17,890
What's up, son?

154
00:09:17,974 --> 00:09:19,934
What are you doing here?
Shouldn't you be at work?

155
00:09:20,017 --> 00:09:23,646
I can't, especially when your bones
are cracking from a mile away!

156
00:09:23,729 --> 00:09:26,399
So, I decided to come over and help you.

157
00:09:26,482 --> 00:09:28,568
You really are full of jokes.

158
00:09:28,651 --> 00:09:32,238
Listen up. This is how I managed to raise
and send you and your siblings to school!

159
00:09:32,321 --> 00:09:35,908
To this day, I'm still
the fastest butcher in this market!

160
00:09:35,992 --> 00:09:38,119
That's why I don't need your help.

161
00:09:38,202 --> 00:09:39,287
- Really?
- Yes!

162
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:40,329
- Then let's see it.
- I don't need it.

163
00:09:40,413 --> 00:09:42,498
- Come on, let's do it.
- Fine, the fastest one wins.

164
00:09:42,582 --> 00:09:44,166
- [Liam] It's a deal.
- Then let's begin.

165
00:09:44,250 --> 00:09:45,126
I'm ready to rumble.

166
00:09:45,209 --> 00:09:46,043
- What do you say?
- Sure.

167
00:09:46,127 --> 00:09:47,545
- It's a speed challenge.
- Okay, then.

168
00:09:47,628 --> 00:09:49,338
- Whoa, whoa, whoa! Let's race, alright?
- Wait,

169
00:09:49,422 --> 00:09:51,424
- I'll take off this white top.
- Hey! No, no…

170
00:09:51,507 --> 00:09:53,050
- Come on, son.
- I'll wear an apron!

171
00:09:53,134 --> 00:09:55,469
- [Abet] Well, hurry up! It's embarrassing.
- [Liam] Huh?

172
00:09:55,553 --> 00:09:57,513
Geez, I had the exact same build ages ago.

173
00:09:57,597 --> 00:09:59,432
Give me that. Get your apron.
That's the one.

174
00:09:59,515 --> 00:10:01,601
[indistinct background chatter]

175
00:10:01,684 --> 00:10:03,227
My goodness.

176
00:10:03,311 --> 00:10:04,937
Alright, come on, come on!

177
00:10:06,397 --> 00:10:07,315
Well, are you ready?

178
00:10:07,398 --> 00:10:08,608
- Are you?
- Oh, I'm ready.

179
00:10:08,691 --> 00:10:10,610
Let's put that to the test.
Stand over there.

180
00:10:10,693 --> 00:10:13,529
- Okay, one, two, three.
- [Abet] Give me a second!

181
00:10:13,613 --> 00:10:14,989
- [Abet] Go!
- [in English] Go, go, go!

182
00:10:17,408 --> 00:10:19,535
[bright piano music playing]

183
00:10:19,619 --> 00:10:21,495
Papa, you'd better retire
and leave the business to me.

184
00:10:21,579 --> 00:10:23,289
- [Liam] I mean, just look at you!
- No, I can do this!

185
00:10:23,372 --> 00:10:25,625
- [Liam] You're moving too slow!
- [Abet] Oh, please!

186
00:10:25,708 --> 00:10:27,293
- [Abet] That's the wrong cut!
- What are you talking about?

187
00:10:27,376 --> 00:10:28,794
- [Abet] It's wrong!
- No, you're doing it wrong!

188
00:10:28,878 --> 00:10:29,920
Don't tell me you forgot my lessons!

189
00:10:30,004 --> 00:10:33,174
[Liam] This is the trendy cut right now!
This is how you do it, Papa!

190
00:10:33,257 --> 00:10:34,467
[chuckles]

191
00:10:39,889 --> 00:10:41,974
- [Abet sighs]
- Well, that's it, Papa.

192
00:10:42,058 --> 00:10:43,643
You're still the best!

193
00:10:43,726 --> 00:10:44,977
Oh, you think I'm the best?

194
00:10:45,061 --> 00:10:46,812
I'm definitely the best and the fastest!

195
00:10:46,896 --> 00:10:49,398
- What did I tell you?
- Yeah, yeah.

196
00:10:49,482 --> 00:10:51,025
Those cuts are all wrong.

197
00:10:51,108 --> 00:10:52,860
Hey, I know you pulled a fast one.

198
00:10:52,943 --> 00:10:54,403
- What do you mean?
- You talked me into this fight

199
00:10:54,487 --> 00:10:56,447
so you could help me with my work.

200
00:10:56,530 --> 00:10:58,032
Well, it worked anyway. Right, Papa?

201
00:10:58,115 --> 00:10:59,450
- It sure did.
- [laughter]

202
00:11:01,452 --> 00:11:02,620
[Suher] Hm?

203
00:11:03,871 --> 00:11:05,122
Go ahead and eat.

204
00:11:05,915 --> 00:11:07,875
I don't have an appetite.

205
00:11:08,542 --> 00:11:10,002
Goodness me.

206
00:11:10,086 --> 00:11:11,921
You need to get your nutrients
or else you'll get sick.

207
00:11:12,004 --> 00:11:14,048
Come on. Just take a bite, okay?

208
00:11:14,131 --> 00:11:17,843
I'll feed you, okay? Here. First bite!

209
00:11:17,927 --> 00:11:20,429
Miss Suher's special! Come on!

210
00:11:20,513 --> 00:11:23,474
[somber music playing]

211
00:11:24,058 --> 00:11:27,436
Well, why do you not have an appetite? Hm?

212
00:11:28,312 --> 00:11:30,356
I've read what other people say.

213
00:11:31,148 --> 00:11:34,902
[voice breaking] They're saying that…

214
00:11:36,487 --> 00:11:39,448
that my parents are criminals.

215
00:11:39,532 --> 00:11:43,244
They are not criminals!
They are kind people!

216
00:11:43,327 --> 00:11:44,787
[sobbing]

217
00:11:47,206 --> 00:11:49,417
Jennie, I believe you.

218
00:11:50,668 --> 00:11:53,462
I believe that they are truly kind.

219
00:11:55,714 --> 00:11:59,718
Your mom and dad are kind. Okay?

220
00:11:59,802 --> 00:12:02,388
Miss Suher believes they are.

221
00:12:02,930 --> 00:12:04,598
Eight hundred and five pesos.

222
00:12:04,682 --> 00:12:07,309
- I'll give it to you for 800 pesos!
- Here's 1,000 pesos!

223
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:08,894
- Why are you shouting?
- I'm not.

224
00:12:08,978 --> 00:12:10,062
What do you mean you're not?

225
00:12:10,146 --> 00:12:12,314
- You did shout! I'm not a liar!
- There's a thousand pesos!

226
00:12:12,398 --> 00:12:14,358
I will give you your change!
Give me a sec!

227
00:12:14,442 --> 00:12:15,985
One thousand? Then your change
is 200 pesos!

228
00:12:16,068 --> 00:12:17,194
Alright then, thank you!

229
00:12:17,278 --> 00:12:21,782
[scoffs] And thank you to you too!
Good Lord! I'll be plagued with bad luck!

230
00:12:21,866 --> 00:12:23,701
[huffs] Calm down.

231
00:12:23,784 --> 00:12:26,203
Calm down. We still have
a lot of work to do.

232
00:12:26,287 --> 00:12:27,913
Oh, just put it over there.

233
00:12:27,997 --> 00:12:31,792
What about the other bags of garlic?

234
00:12:31,876 --> 00:12:35,921
Oh, madam, delivery will be free for those

235
00:12:36,005 --> 00:12:38,841
who are gorgeous like Auntie Bang!

236
00:12:38,924 --> 00:12:40,426
Auntie!

237
00:12:40,509 --> 00:12:43,596
Oh, Ryan! You're so mischievous!

238
00:12:43,679 --> 00:12:44,763
Oh, you!

239
00:12:44,847 --> 00:12:47,808
- [in English] I missed you! [grunting]
- Stop it!

240
00:12:47,892 --> 00:12:49,643
- Same old, alright?
- [gentle music playing]

241
00:12:49,727 --> 00:12:51,896
I'll do the selling, you do the repacking.

242
00:12:51,979 --> 00:12:53,606
Do you still know how to? You do.

243
00:12:53,689 --> 00:12:55,357
You'll manage. Just put that here.

244
00:12:55,441 --> 00:12:57,026
- Goodness me.
- [Bang] Got it?

245
00:12:57,985 --> 00:13:00,070
Auntie, if only you know…

246
00:13:00,154 --> 00:13:01,280
- Hm? What?
- [sighs]

247
00:13:01,363 --> 00:13:03,657
I missed this life so much.

248
00:13:04,783 --> 00:13:07,328
Simple. Not much trouble at all.

249
00:13:07,411 --> 00:13:11,081
[clicks tongue] From the way
you're speaking, there's like…

250
00:13:11,749 --> 00:13:13,959
an air of maturity on it.

251
00:13:14,043 --> 00:13:15,419
It doesn't suit you!

252
00:13:15,503 --> 00:13:19,006
[gentle music playing]

253
00:13:19,089 --> 00:13:20,132
Why?

254
00:13:22,134 --> 00:13:23,719
Are you having a hard time at work?

255
00:13:25,888 --> 00:13:29,350
Well, there's no easy job anyway. Plus…

256
00:13:30,017 --> 00:13:32,186
I've always dreamed of this.

257
00:13:32,269 --> 00:13:35,064
So, don't worry. I'm alright.

258
00:13:35,147 --> 00:13:36,815
[clicks tongue] That's fair.

259
00:13:36,899 --> 00:13:41,570
Ever since you were a kid,
I knew you wanted to be a policeman.

260
00:13:44,323 --> 00:13:45,741
Don't worry.

261
00:13:47,284 --> 00:13:51,830
When you get stressed with work,
you can always come home.

262
00:13:51,914 --> 00:13:53,165
Lend me a hand here at the shop.

263
00:13:53,249 --> 00:13:55,709
- Really?
- You'll be able to relax, too.

264
00:13:55,793 --> 00:13:57,920
- It's relaxing to sell!
- [laughs]

265
00:13:58,003 --> 00:14:00,756
And tell me all about your missions.

266
00:14:00,839 --> 00:14:02,174
- [laughs]
- You can, right?

267
00:14:06,720 --> 00:14:10,599
Rolan. Look at what happened
at San Aurelio Street.

268
00:14:11,559 --> 00:14:14,436
It's obvious that our government
no longer has any control

269
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:18,065
over the entry
of illegal firearms in our country.

270
00:14:18,566 --> 00:14:22,528
Crimes are getting worse
due to this failure of an administration.

271
00:14:25,322 --> 00:14:27,449
You know, I think…

272
00:14:28,576 --> 00:14:30,744
we need to intervene.

273
00:14:31,620 --> 00:14:35,708
If not, our country is doomed.

274
00:14:35,791 --> 00:14:38,252
[grim music playing]

275
00:14:38,335 --> 00:14:40,629
The state of things right now
is disappointing.

276
00:14:41,922 --> 00:14:43,841
Do you remember when we were still cadets?

277
00:14:45,259 --> 00:14:47,094
Our idealism was extreme.

278
00:14:48,178 --> 00:14:49,805
But look at what's happening right now.

279
00:14:50,764 --> 00:14:53,225
The people in power

280
00:14:54,268 --> 00:14:55,686
are powerless themselves.

281
00:14:58,689 --> 00:15:02,151
Whatever can we do about this, Vicente?

282
00:15:03,068 --> 00:15:06,071
You know, I remembered
something you told me before.

283
00:15:06,780 --> 00:15:11,285
About the power us in the service possess.

284
00:15:12,036 --> 00:15:13,370
What was it again?

285
00:15:14,371 --> 00:15:15,539
Ah!

286
00:15:16,457 --> 00:15:17,750
I said…

287
00:15:18,375 --> 00:15:23,589
I believe that the one who truly
runs and controls this country…

288
00:15:25,049 --> 00:15:26,842
is the Armed Forces.

289
00:15:27,384 --> 00:15:29,803
When the military join forces
with one another

290
00:15:29,887 --> 00:15:32,556
and withdraws their support altogether

291
00:15:32,640 --> 00:15:34,558
from the current government,

292
00:15:35,684 --> 00:15:38,103
the administration is sure to crumble.

293
00:15:38,896 --> 00:15:42,316
[sinister music playing]

294
00:15:42,399 --> 00:15:43,233
That's right.

295
00:15:44,401 --> 00:15:46,028
I thought of that, too.

296
00:15:46,654 --> 00:15:49,698
Why would we let the Philippines
fall into chaos

297
00:15:50,407 --> 00:15:53,327
when we have the ability
to straighten it out anyway?

298
00:15:55,204 --> 00:15:57,957
Change is really upon us, Vicente.

299
00:15:58,040 --> 00:15:58,916
[Madrigal] Mmm.

300
00:15:58,999 --> 00:16:00,209
[in English] I agree.

301
00:16:01,085 --> 00:16:03,504
Can I count on you
when that happens, Rolan?

302
00:16:06,340 --> 00:16:10,761
Absolutely. Vicente, you can count on it.

303
00:16:11,261 --> 00:16:16,350
[dramatic sting]

304
00:16:16,433 --> 00:16:17,559
[glasses clink]

305
00:16:19,103 --> 00:16:22,856
[tense music playing]

306
00:16:25,818 --> 00:16:26,777
I'll go first, 'kay?

307
00:16:26,860 --> 00:16:28,737
I wonder what's the news on Agent Angeles.

308
00:16:28,821 --> 00:16:30,489
I still haven't heard anything about her.

309
00:16:31,448 --> 00:16:33,909
What about Agent Espina?
I wonder how he's doing.

310
00:16:34,618 --> 00:16:36,245
I haven't heard anything about him either.

311
00:16:40,082 --> 00:16:41,250
Hey, blockheads!

312
00:16:42,751 --> 00:16:44,044
Useless bastards!

313
00:16:44,128 --> 00:16:45,587
- You're all useless!
- [thudding]

314
00:16:45,671 --> 00:16:47,339
These rascals…

315
00:16:47,423 --> 00:16:48,424
- Get over here!
- Stop your nonsense!

316
00:16:49,466 --> 00:16:50,300
[officer 1] Stop right there!

317
00:16:51,844 --> 00:16:52,886
- [officer 1] You little!
- [officer 2] Brats!

318
00:16:53,846 --> 00:16:54,888
When I catch them…

319
00:16:55,889 --> 00:16:57,725
- They've done it now.
- Are they out of it?

320
00:16:57,808 --> 00:16:59,018
Let's go!

321
00:16:59,101 --> 00:17:03,647
[morose music playing]

322
00:17:05,190 --> 00:17:06,191
[door squeaks open]

323
00:17:06,275 --> 00:17:08,610
Did you guys hear
about what happened with Jardin?

324
00:17:09,236 --> 00:17:10,237
[Liam] Yes, sir.

325
00:17:10,320 --> 00:17:12,614
The audacity to do it
right in front of the gate!

326
00:17:13,407 --> 00:17:16,618
The nerve! People no longer fear us.

327
00:17:17,369 --> 00:17:19,288
Not only do they not fear us anymore,

328
00:17:19,371 --> 00:17:21,248
they don't respect us anymore, too.

329
00:17:21,331 --> 00:17:25,419
What's worse is that if those kids
have no problem doing this,

330
00:17:25,502 --> 00:17:27,421
what more those criminals?

331
00:17:27,504 --> 00:17:30,966
Instead of getting more peaceful,
things have become more chaotic.

332
00:17:33,093 --> 00:17:35,763
I saw it, sir.
It's all on the news already.

333
00:17:36,638 --> 00:17:38,098
[in English] We're under a lot of fire.

334
00:17:39,016 --> 00:17:42,061
It's no wonder that people
are attacking us.

335
00:17:46,982 --> 00:17:48,192
[Liam] Sir!

336
00:17:48,275 --> 00:17:49,485
- [door clicks shut]
- Sir, have you recovered?

337
00:17:50,486 --> 00:17:52,196
Aren't you supposed to be resting, sir?

338
00:17:53,906 --> 00:17:55,616
We still have a lot to finish.

339
00:17:57,451 --> 00:18:00,162
There are innocent lives still in danger.

340
00:18:00,245 --> 00:18:01,497
There's no way I'll be able to rest.

341
00:18:02,956 --> 00:18:05,709
All right, sir.
We're only missing Agent Angeles now.

342
00:18:06,752 --> 00:18:07,753
Where is she?

343
00:18:09,463 --> 00:18:10,756
Running late?

344
00:18:11,423 --> 00:18:13,425
[stirring music playing]

345
00:18:13,509 --> 00:18:14,635
She hasn't shown herself

346
00:18:14,718 --> 00:18:17,096
ever since the explosion
at San Aurelio Street.

347
00:18:28,398 --> 00:18:32,444
[suspenseful music playing]

348
00:18:54,716 --> 00:19:00,305
[music intensifies, fades]

349
00:19:02,516 --> 00:19:05,644
[grim music playing]

350
00:19:09,231 --> 00:19:10,732
[sighs]

351
00:19:10,816 --> 00:19:12,442
Yes, General?

352
00:19:13,026 --> 00:19:14,403
Were you able to contact Lara?

353
00:19:14,987 --> 00:19:16,697
Not yet, General.

354
00:19:17,489 --> 00:19:19,116
[sighs]

355
00:19:21,785 --> 00:19:22,619
‪[dramatic sting]

356
00:19:30,210 --> 00:19:32,462
[line ringing]

357
00:19:35,132 --> 00:19:38,135
[voice prompt, in English] <i>The subscriber</i>
<i>cannot be reached. Please try--</i>

358
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:52,191
[voice prompt, in English] <i>The subscriber</i>
<i>cannot be reached. Please try--</i>

359
00:19:57,946 --> 00:20:01,658
[voice prompt, in English] <i>The subscriber</i>
<i>cannot be reached. Please try again later.</i>

360
00:20:01,742 --> 00:20:05,037
Lara! Where on earth are you?

361
00:20:05,954 --> 00:20:07,080
[line ringing]

362
00:20:07,164 --> 00:20:08,373
Answer me.

363
00:20:11,335 --> 00:20:13,670
[voice prompt, in English]
<i>The subscriber cannot be reached.</i>

364
00:20:13,754 --> 00:20:19,218
[suspenseful music playing]

365
00:20:21,970 --> 00:20:24,097
Even our other members were puzzled

366
00:20:24,181 --> 00:20:27,184
about her sudden disappearance
after the explosion.

367
00:20:28,268 --> 00:20:30,354
There are only two possible reasons why.

368
00:20:31,104 --> 00:20:33,565
It's either her life
is in danger right now

369
00:20:34,149 --> 00:20:37,402
or she blew the bus up herself
and now she's hiding.

370
00:20:38,528 --> 00:20:42,616
[ominous music playing]

371
00:20:45,535 --> 00:20:47,746
Whatever it is,
only she can give us an answer.

372
00:20:47,829 --> 00:20:50,165
That's why we have to find her.

373
00:20:51,833 --> 00:20:53,961
You know, even if I'm suspicious of Lara,

374
00:20:55,754 --> 00:20:57,589
I still hope that she's safe.

375
00:20:59,883 --> 00:21:01,051
[sighs]

376
00:21:01,134 --> 00:21:02,552
We went through a lot
of missions together.

377
00:21:05,138 --> 00:21:07,057
We went through a lot of things.

378
00:21:07,933 --> 00:21:08,976
[Marcus inhales]

379
00:21:09,059 --> 00:21:12,771
I genuinely trusted her
because we both lost someone.

380
00:21:15,732 --> 00:21:16,984
Lost someone?

381
00:21:17,567 --> 00:21:19,987
[emotional music playing]

382
00:21:20,070 --> 00:21:22,656
[breathes heavily]

383
00:21:22,739 --> 00:21:26,243
I lost my father and brother.

384
00:21:26,994 --> 00:21:28,203
Meanwhile Lara…

385
00:21:30,330 --> 00:21:31,957
lost both her parents.

386
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:34,293
[suspenseful sting]

387
00:21:34,376 --> 00:21:37,045
You know, I really trusted Lara…

388
00:21:38,505 --> 00:21:40,507
before the incident on Damai Island.

389
00:21:45,012 --> 00:21:47,639
What… happened to her parents?

390
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:50,726
[inhales sharply]

391
00:21:50,809 --> 00:21:53,186
Both of Lara's parents were doctors.

392
00:21:54,438 --> 00:21:56,106
They died together

393
00:21:56,690 --> 00:22:00,152
in an ambush
during a medical mission they were on.

394
00:22:01,361 --> 00:22:02,946
[somber music playing]

395
00:22:03,030 --> 00:22:04,573
Lara became an orphan at a young age.

396
00:22:06,783 --> 00:22:08,785
And so General Carillo took her in.

397
00:22:08,869 --> 00:22:10,996
["Maninindigan" by Marko Rudio playing]

398
00:22:11,079 --> 00:22:14,916
♪ <i>If the law is only for a select few</i> ♪

399
00:22:16,543 --> 00:22:18,879
♪ <i>And justice is</i> ♪

400
00:22:18,962 --> 00:22:24,384
[tense music playing]

401
00:22:47,532 --> 00:22:50,660
[tense music intensifies]

402
00:22:54,831 --> 00:22:56,249
[drawer clicks shut]

403
00:23:29,116 --> 00:23:31,409
What's with it that made you smile?

404
00:23:44,297 --> 00:23:46,591
[music turns pensive]

405
00:23:46,675 --> 00:23:50,720
[papers rustle]

406
00:23:55,016 --> 00:23:57,477
Both of Lara's parents were doctors.

407
00:23:58,645 --> 00:24:00,313
They died together

408
00:24:00,897 --> 00:24:04,359
in an ambush
during a medical mission they were on.

409
00:24:04,442 --> 00:24:07,529
[pensive music continues]

410
00:24:22,377 --> 00:24:24,880
[Espina] <i>Are you General Carillo's</i>
<i>accomplice, Lara?</i>

411
00:24:25,839 --> 00:24:29,467
<i>Or is he trying to silence you,</i>
<i>just like his other victims?</i>

412
00:24:29,551 --> 00:24:33,513
[pensive music playing]

413
00:24:33,597 --> 00:24:37,726
[dramatic stinging]

414
00:24:46,401 --> 00:24:49,154
[Marcus] <i>Lara hasn't reported</i>
<i>to the headquarters for days.</i>

415
00:24:49,237 --> 00:24:51,948
Lara just disappeared after the explosion.

416
00:24:52,032 --> 00:24:53,074
Lara is a grown-up.

417
00:24:53,158 --> 00:24:55,493
I don't need to know
where she is all the time.

418
00:24:56,661 --> 00:24:58,079
[Felix] <i>Where are you, Lara?</i>

419
00:24:58,163 --> 00:24:59,998
<i>What are you really planning?</i>

420
00:25:00,081 --> 00:25:01,791
<i>Why did you disappear?</i>

421
00:25:01,875 --> 00:25:03,835
We need to stop

422
00:25:03,919 --> 00:25:07,297
all of General Carillo's evil schemes.

423
00:25:07,380 --> 00:25:09,883
It's hard to go near him. He can sense
when someone's plotting against him.

424
00:25:09,966 --> 00:25:13,845
[Usman] <i>Mustapha and General Carillo</i>
<i>will have a face-off.</i>

425
00:25:13,929 --> 00:25:16,014
That's your chance.

426
00:25:16,097 --> 00:25:17,307
[Manuel] <i>Tell me the truth.</i>

427
00:25:17,390 --> 00:25:19,809
Did you set off the detonator?

428
00:25:20,310 --> 00:25:22,103
[in English] Felix, answer me!

429
00:25:22,187 --> 00:25:23,521
[screams]

430
00:25:23,605 --> 00:25:26,441
[Teresa] <i>I want to keep hoping</i>
<i>that my son is still alive.</i>

431
00:25:27,275 --> 00:25:29,194
Allan. He might be Gabriel.

432
00:25:29,277 --> 00:25:31,029
[Teresa] <i>He's my lost son, Jamilah.</i>

433
00:25:31,112 --> 00:25:32,489
<i>I need an answer.</i>

434
00:25:33,490 --> 00:25:37,744
[Jamilah] <i>If she does that,</i>
<i>Jalil's plan would be ruined.</i>
